value.value: A mining process during which rock or mineral deposits are extracted from the terrestrial surface layers of an astronomical body.

definition.value: A mining process which occurs in a marine ecosystem.

value.value: A mining process during which coal is extracted from the rocky portion of an astronomical body.

definition.value: This may be either terrestrial or marine.

value.value: A mining process during which metal ores and minerals that lie near the terrestrial surface of an astronomical body are extracted by removing the overlying material and breaking and loading the ore.

A land use process during which terrestrial environments are modified such that they can grow crop plants or allow the rearing of animals to provide food, fiber, medicines, or other products used by humans.

"Agriculture includes horticulture, fruit growing, seed growing, dairy farming, the breeding and keeping of livestock (including any creature kept for the production of food, wool, skins or fur), the use of land as grazing land, meadow land, osier land, market gardens and nursery grounds, and the use of woodlands where that use is ancillary to the farming of land for other agricultural purposes."

label.value: usage of an environment for recreation

value.value: A planned environmental usage process during which humans access an environment in order to promote the refreshment of their physical and psychological health through relaxation and leisure activities.

label.value: usage of an environment for transportation

value.value: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment facilitates the movement of materials and material objects (persons or goods) from place to place, typically with the assistance of a vehicle.

label.value: usage of an environment for infrastructure and utilities

value.value: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports 1) enterprises concerned with the provision to the public of essentials, such as electricity or water or 2) the basic network or foundation of capital facilities or community investments which are necessary to support economic and community activities.

label.value: usage of an environment for residential activity

value.value: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports the settlement and dwelling of a community of humans.

definition.value: This class does not include environments which are primarily used for commerce or industry.

label.value: usage of an environment for community and social services

value.value: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports welfare activities organised by the state or a local authority and carried out by trained personnel.

definition.value: Services include those provided by health care facilities, places of religious worship, educational facilities, police stations, fire stations, coastguard facilities, public sanitation, non-human animal welfare services, detention services, and other public services.

label.value: usage of an environment for retail activity

value.value: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports the sale of goods to ultimate consumers, usually in small quantities.

definition.value: This class includes activities carried out in shops, showrooms, cafes, travel agents, hairdressers, facilities providing financial and professional services, restaurants, public houses, and bars.

label.value: usage of an environment for defence

value.value: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports activities which aim to protect citizens or any geographical area by preparing for or by using military means to resist the attack of an enemy.

definition.value: This class includes activities carried out in defence establishments, including camps, airfields, and live firing training areas. It excludes sites where defence personnel reside, such as barracks.

label.value: usage of an environment for industry

value.value: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports manufacturing facilities producing commodities that are sold with the expectation of recovering the total cost of production.

definition.value: This class includes environments used to support the facilities engaged with a broad variety of manufacturing activities from food and tobacco, to textiles, metals, vehicles, and chemicals.

label.value: usage of an environment for business

value.value: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports facilities associated with commerce or the earning of a livelihood through means other than manufacturing or the provision of a public service.

definition.value: This class includes activities carried out in commercial offices, meeting centres, art studios, recording studios, film sets, warehouses, and distribution centres.
A habitat which supports the persistence and growth of a population of Calyptra moths and which overlaps mesic meadows and edges and clearings in vegetated areas.
A mountain which is located on land and which is bounded by an atmosphere or outer space.

value.value: A mountain that is part of a polar environment.
A mountain that is part of a temperate environment.
A mountain that is part of a tropical environment.

A montane forest ecosystem which 1) is evergreen, 2) present on mountains where there is frequent cloud and mist cover, 3) which has a large proportion of ferns and mosses in its plant communities, growing on all tree trunks and branches present in the ecosystem, and 3) harvests aerosolised water and adds it to the terrestrial water supply.
A visible mass of water droplets or ice crystals suspended in the air at or near a planetary surface, formed when humid air cools rapidly.

definition.value: This class refers only to mist formed by materials primarily composed of water. Mist is less dense than fog, and visibility is typically greater than one kilometre.

value.value: A mountain which has a maximum elevation greater than 2500 metres above sea level.

definition.value: On Earth, mountains in this category cross the atmospheric oxycline above which oxygen concentrations fall below the physiological tolerance threshold of most humans. Note that the threshold elevations are inconsistent between the various reports which list this classification: while some have overlapping thresholds, others are non-overlapping. The latter model is used in ENVO for coherence and to adhere to the Kapos et al. 2000 reference.

value.value: A mountain which has a maximum elevation between 300 and 2499 metres above sea level and slopes greater than or equal to two degrees of inclination.

definition.value: On Earth, mountains in this category are below the atmospheric oxycline above which oxygen concentrations fall below the physiological tolerance threshold of most humans. Note that the threshold elevations are inconsistent between the various reports which list this classification: while some have overlapping thresholds, others are non-overlapping. The latter model is used in ENVO for coherence and to adhere to the Kapos et al. 2000 reference.

value.value: A high-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation greater than 4500 metres above sea level.
A high-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 3500 and 4500 metres above sea level.
A high-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 2500 and 3500 metres above sea level.
A mid-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 1500 and 2499 metres above sea level and a slope greater than or equal to two degrees.

A mid-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 1000 and 1499 metres above sea level and either 1) a slope greater than or equal to five degrees or 2) a local elevation range, within a 7 kilometre radius, of greater than 300 metres above sea level.
A mid-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 300 and 999 metres above sea level and a local elevation range, within a 7 kilometre radius, of greater than 300 metres above sea level.
An elevated inner basin or plateau surrounded by mountains, but not - itself - a mountain.

definition.value: This is an odd class, as it's not a mountain in itself but is used to classify elevated basins and plateaus surrounded by mountains.

value.value: An ecosystem which overlaps those areas of the foreshore and seabed that are exposed to the air at low tide and submerged at high tide.

definition.value: These semantics link with those of environmental zones. Use this class to refer to the ecosystem rather than the area that it occupies.
A system of constructed and manufactured products which are used by humans to produce data, information, or knowledge about material, immaterial, or processual entities.
An observing system which generates long-term data about one or more entities of interest, typically using standardised methodology.

value.value: An observatory system which includes components used to generate (meta)genomic, (meta)transcriptomic, (meta)proteomic, metabolomic, and other omic data, information, and knowledge.

definition.value: A liquid astronomical body part which is continuous and is delimited by physical discontinuities or non-liquid boundaries.
A part of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of liquid material.
A part of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of gaseous material.

value.value: A part of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of fluid.
A building which is primarily used for the long-term habitation of humans.
A prison facility which is owned and operated by a state.

A tornado is an aeroform consisting of at least one rapidly rotating column of air that is in contact with both the surface of an astronomical body and pendant from within or beneath a cumulonimbus or cumulus cloud.

definition.value: This class refers to tornados on Earth, but can be used as the basis for a more generalised class for tornados which a composed of gaseous materials other than air.
A surface layer where the solid or liquid material of an astronomical body comes into contact with an atmosphere or outer space.
a useful class: this can be used to define sub-terrestrial and sub-marine entities

value.value: A fire whirl is a whirlwind induced by the contraction and rotation of intense, rising heat and turbulent, eddying air masses resulting from a large fire and made up of a core of burning matter surrounded by a rotating pocket of air.

definition.value: Note that this not a sublcass of "tornado": this is a different phenomenon formed as a result of  convection induced by fire.

value.value: A tornado which comprises two or more columns of spinning air rotating about their own axis and at the same time around a common center.

A tornado which a) is not associated with a mesocyclone and is thus relatively weak and short-lived, b) is centred on a small, smooth condensation funnel which often does not reach the planetary surface, and c) forms a distinctively laminar cloud of dust when it makes contact with the land.
A tornado which connects a cumulus or cumulonimbus cloud to a body of water, often transporting water from that water body along the spiraling winds constituting  its vortex.

definition.value: Wikipedia notes that there is disagreement over whether to classify waterspouts as true tornadoes.
